AU  - Battalio, Raymond C.
AU  - Beil, Richard O.
T1  - Strategic Uncertainty, Equilibrium Selection, and Coordination Failure in Average Opinion Games*
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937932
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 106
IS  - 3
SP  - 885
EP  - 910
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Deductive equilibrium analysis often fails to provide a unique equilibrium solution in many situations of strategic interdependence. Consequently, a theory of equilibrium selection would be a useful complement to the theory of equilibrium points. A salient equilibrium selection principle would allow decision makers to implement a mutual best response outcome. This paper uses the experimental method to examine the salience of payoff-dominance, security, and historical precedents in related average opinion games. The systematic and, hence, predictable behavior observed in the experiments suggests that it should be possible to construct an accurate theory of equilibrium selection.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937932
ER  - 



